Addressing a comment I inevitably get whenever I post about my thigh lift. 

I like to try to provide accurate and transparent information to you all and because this comes up quite often, I thought I’d speak about it. 

Lipedema is a chronic condition that causes a buildup of fat in the arms and legs. It causes pain, swelling and unusual bruising. It can also have characteristics like unusual texture beneath the skin, like peas or walnuts. It’s different than cellulite which is just that uneven dimpled skin, but it looks similar. 

The key difference is that cellulite is a cosmetic condition that doesn’t lead to other health issues while Lipedema needs to be treated or it can progress and lead to pain and mobility issues. I have several friends on Instagram that do battle this condition and it can be brutal both physically and mentally so it’s nothing to take lightly if you think you might have it. 

As always, I am not a medical professional, and neither are the majority of the people on this app. Looking at a picture of someone and diagnosing them with a serious condition really shouldn’t be a thing. Seek care from the professionals, as they’re the ones that have years of education and can properly diagnose things like this.

Everyone’s situation is different, and my case as I show in the video, I still have some loose skin and cellulite, and I’m aware that the appearance of my thighs isn’t perfect. But I’m learning to be okay with that. I’ve been through a lot and have learned that plastic surgery doesn’t fix everything after major damage has been done. 

PS I don’t need a fascia blaster either. 😉

Let’s get real for a moment. Here on Instagram people only show what they want you to see. The reality of gaining and losing weight is that most of the time, you are left with some degree of loose skin pretty much everywhere. Most of mine was on my stomach, arms and thighs which is why I focused on those areas for skin removal when I had my plastic surgery. 

But I still have loose skin. It’s mainly on my backside/outer thighs. I’ve been through a lot of surgery this past year so it’s really not on my radar right now to fix this. It doesn’t really bother me that much anyway. 

I’m showing this because this is the reality after massive weight loss. Excess skin removal from weight loss patients are usually done in multiple stages and several surgeries. It’s a lot to deal with quite honestly and not everything is going to be perfect. But you know what? That’s okay! 

I’m fit and healthy and never though I would be where I am today from where I started. 

Today I’m going to celebrate ALL of me including that little bit extra junk in the trunk! 🥰

Hi, I’m Steph! I lost 116 lbs after weight loss surgery (vsg) in 2019. I completely changed the way I eat and I incorporated fitness into my life which has been instrumental in changing my body and keeping the weight off. 

I share my story so openly because I want to help others who are struggling with their weight. I know how hard it can be, and I want you to know that you’re not alone.

I’ve learned a lot on my journey, and I want to share some of the things that have helped me the most.

First, it’s important to be patient. It takes time to lose weight and keep it off. Don’t get discouraged if your weight loss is slower than you’d like. I lost slow and steady for 15 months before hitting my goal. Your timeline is your own so don’t compare your journey to anyone else’s. 

Second, it’s important to find a support system. Having people who support you and encourage you can make a big difference. 

Finally, it’s important to be kind to yourself. It’s progress over perfection so just keep going, even if you had a bad day.  You don’t have to be perfect all the time, or sabotage yourself when the day doesn’t go as planned. Just move on and try to be better in the next hour, the next day, the next week. Whatever it takes. 

I know that a weight loss journey can be a challenge, but it’s definitely possible. 

If I can do it, you can do it too.

***For educational purposes***

This is what a breast lift with no implants looks like. Obviously I’m going to cover up, but no bra here and everything is facing in the right direction iykyk. 

You can see in my before surgery photo that I had enough volume to accomplish this. After weight loss and two kids, I’m very lucky that they didn’t completely deflate, although there was plenty of loose skin. Sometimes, implants are needed because there simple isn’t enough volume or breast tissue left.

I wanted an athletic and smaller look so this was a perfect choice for me. 

My surgeon did use an internal mesh bra called Galaflex which is bioreabsorbable, that helps reinforce the breast tissue until the collagen builds up and then it’s reabsorbed by the body (at about 18-24 months). 

For reference, I was a 38DDD before plastic surgery and am now a 32C.

✨Remember who you were before they told you who to be. ✨

The impossible task of trying to be everything the media tells you, or what you see on TV, on social media or in magazines is exhausting. At 4 years out from the beginning of my (most current) journey, I’m realizing that the years and years of hating my body is harder to get rid of than the weight that I thought losing would solve. 

All this to say that when someone says they’re struggling, it doesn’t always mean they’re struggling with regaining weight or falling back into old habits. Sometimes that struggle is battling the old wounds that are deeply engrained in our being. Working on self love is so important on this journey.

Hi my name is Steph and I’ve lost and maintained a 116 lbs weight loss. 👋

I thought I would reintroduce myself and give you a quick rundown of my story. 

In 2019 is had vsg after a life long battle with yo-yo dieting and failure to maintain a healthy lifestyle for any long period of time. 🪀

I lost the weight and was left with a good amount of excess skin, which I had removed in two separate rounds of plastic surgery. 💪👙
 
What’s different this time around is that I’m focused, I did the physical AND the mental work, and I realized that things don’t always have to be perfect. Letting go of perfection has given me the freedom to live a more balanced life and also give myself some grace when I might slip up. 🖤🤍

Every day might not go as planned but the important thing to remember is that there is always room to improve and do better but I don’t beat myself up about it. This helps me not spiral out of control. 🌀 

If your kids, your husband or wife, or your best friend messed up, would you completely give up on them? No, so why would you do that to yourself? 

Remember, progress, not perfection. Embrace the journey, give yourself grace, and keep moving forward. You’ve got this! 💪🌟
